questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput Java 21 service was migrated from Platform Threads to Virtual Threads to handle more concurrent connections. During peak load, you observe that the throughput drops significantly and CPU utilization on the carrier threads is unusually high, while the OS thread count remains low. You find the following snippet in the codebase: 

java
public class DataService {
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public String processRequest(String id) {
        synchronized (this) {
            return bffClient.fetchData(id); // Performs blocking network I/O
        }
    }
}

You are debugging a Spring Boot application where a developer attempted to offload a database write to a background thread to improve API response times. They used the following implementation:

java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Autowired private OrderRepository repository;

    @Transactional
    public void placeOrder(Order order) {
        repository.save(order);
        CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> {
            updateInventory(order);
        });
    }

    private void updateInventory(Order order) {
        // Logic to update inventory table
    }
}

In production, users report that inventory updates are frequently missing even when orders are successfully saved.

You are investigating a memory leak in a service that aggregates data from multiple microservices using `CompletableFuture`. The code looks like this:

java
public CompletableFuture<Response> aggregate() {
    var task1 = serviceA.call();
    var task2 = serviceB.call();

    return CompletableFuture.allOf(task1, task2)
        .thenApply(v -> new Response(task1.join(), task2.join()));
}

Under heavy load, the `ForkJoinPool.commonPool()` becomes saturated, and the application's heap usage grows until an `OutOfMemoryError` occurs. Thread dumps show thousands of threads waiting on `CompletableFuture.join()`.
